    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-12-07T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-12-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="1138"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1138">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">701.60d61/18: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Sweden</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Sterling</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Stockholm</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-12-07">December 7,
                            1939</date>.<lb/>[Received December 7—6:52 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>268. Following by telephone for Department from Helsinki.</p>
                <quote rend="blockquote">
                    <p>“409. December 7, noon. Secretary General Finnish Foreign Office has just
                        telephoned me by direction Minister for Foreign Affairs stating that Finnish
                        Minister and Legation personnel Moscow expect to leave Moscow for Berlin via
                            Dunaburg<note n="20" xml:id="d1138fn20">Daugavpils, Dvinsk.</note>
                        today. He stated German Ambassador as Dean of Diplomatic Corps had been
                        requested to take <pb facs="1037" n="1025" xml:id="pg_1025"/> charge of
                        Finnish interests and had referred matter to his Government but German
                        Ambassador doubted it would authorize such action. He reminded me that
                        Finnish Government had previously asked Swedish Government to take over its
                        interests but Soviet Government had refused.</p>
                    <p>Secretary General now inquires whether American Embassy Moscow could be
                        authorized to take charge of Finnish interests or at least of Finnish
                        Legation building. I said I would refer matter to you immediately.
                        Schoenfeld.”</p>
                </quote>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Sterling</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
